title: Hong-Kong-born Cheung on Asia-Pacific leaderboard with 64
text:
Hong-Kong-born Cheung moves up the leaderboard with 6-under 64 at Asia-Pacific Amateur THE ASSOCIATED PRESS   1:51   1:51   
Subjects: 
East Asia (691) 

HONG KONG â€” Hong Kong-born Matthew Cheung moved up the leaderboard at the Asia-Pacific Amateur on Friday with a second-round 6-under 64 at wind-swept Clearwater Bay. 
Cheung, who was raised in Brisbane, Australia and attends Oklahoma City University, sat two strokes behind clubhouse leader She Zihan of China, who shot 66 Friday and had a two-round total of 7-under 133. 
Both had morning rounds on the picturesque peninsula course that overlooks the South China Sea. 
Jin Cheng of China, who led by two strokes after the first round with a course-record 62, had an afternoon start Friday. 
Cheung enjoyed the gallery support during his round that included five birdies, a bogey on 17 and an eagle on the par-5 18th. 
"I was born here, a lot of my family and friends are here, and I still consider this home," Cheung said. 
Nick Voke of New Zealand, who completed his first-round 64 on Friday morning due to a thunderstorm delay Thursday, shot 71 Friday and was at 5-under, level with Cheung. 
Defending champion Antonio Murdaca of Australia shot 70 Friday and was 1-under. 
"People are losing balls left and right," Murdaca, who won last year at Royal Melbourne, said of the tough morning conditions. 
Guan Tianlang of China, the 2012 champion, shot 73 Friday and was at 1-over 141 and expected to make the cut. 
The tournament champion receives an invitation to next year's Masters. The champion and runner-up receive a place in the final round of qualifying for the 2016 British Open at Royal Troon.
